<tasks>

<task type="auto">
  <name>Task 1: Migration — add is_super_admin + super admin RLS policy</name>
  <files>supabase/migrations/20260316100000_add_super_admin.sql</files>
  <action>
Create a new migration file with two operations:

1. Add `is_super_admin` column to `public.users`:
   ```sql
   ALTER TABLE public.users
     ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS is_super_admin boolean NOT NULL DEFAULT false;
   ```
   This is non-breaking — all existing users get `false` via DEFAULT (DB-01, DB-02).

2. Add a super admin SELECT policy on the `events` table so `fetchAllEvents()` works through RLS:
   ```sql
   CREATE POLICY "Super admins can select all events"
     ON events FOR SELECT TO authenticated
     USING (
       EXISTS (
         SELECT 1 FROM public.users u
         WHERE u.id = auth.uid() AND u.is_super_admin = true
       )
     );
   ```
   NOTE: The user said "skip RLS changes" but research identified this is REQUIRED for CTX-02 (super admin fetch all events). Without it, `fetchAllEvents()` returns empty for super admins who don't own events. This is the minimal necessary addition — not a full RLS rework.

3. Also add super admin SELECT policies on `invitations`, `message_logs`, and `automation_settings` using the same pattern — so when a super admin switches to an event they don't own, dashboard data loads correctly:
   ```sql
   CREATE POLICY "Super admins can select all invitations"
     ON invitations FOR SELECT TO authenticated
     USING (EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM public.users u WHERE u.id = auth.uid() AND u.is_super_admin = true));

   CREATE POLICY "Super admins can update all invitations"
     ON invitations FOR UPDATE TO authenticated
     USING (EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM public.users u WHERE u.id = auth.uid() AND u.is_super_admin = true));

   CREATE POLICY "Super admins can select all message_logs"
     ON message_logs FOR SELECT TO authenticated
     USING (EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM public.users u WHERE u.id = auth.uid() AND u.is_super_admin = true));

   CREATE POLICY "Super admins can select all automation_settings"
     ON automation_settings FOR SELECT TO authenticated
     USING (EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM public.users u WHERE u.id = auth.uid() AND u.is_super_admin = true));

   CREATE POLICY "Super admins can update all automation_settings"
     ON automation_settings FOR UPDATE TO authenticated
     USING (EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM public.users u WHERE u.id = auth.uid() AND u.is_super_admin = true));

   CREATE POLICY "Super admins can update all events"
     ON events FOR UPDATE TO authenticated
     USING (EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM public.users u WHERE u.id = auth.uid() AND u.is_super_admin = true));
   ```

Also add a SELECT policy on `public.users` so AuthContext can read `is_super_admin` for the current user (the existing policy "Users can view own profile" already covers `id = auth.uid()` — so this is already handled, no additional policy needed).
  </action>
  <verify>
    <automated>cat supabase/migrations/20260316100000_add_super_admin.sql | grep -c "is_super_admin\|Super admin"</automated>
  </verify>
  <done>Migration file exists with is_super_admin column addition and super admin RLS SELECT/UPDATE policies on events, invitations, message_logs, automation_settings</done>
</task>

<task type="auto">
  <name>Task 2: Query functions + AuthContext extension</name>
  <files>src/lib/supabase.js, src/contexts/AuthContext.tsx</files>
  <action>
**In `src/lib/supabase.js`** — add two new exported functions (keep existing `fetchEventForUser` intact for now; Plan 02 will stop calling it):

1. `fetchEventsForUser()` — fetches all events for the authenticated user via `user_events` join:
   ```javascript
   export const fetchEventsForUser = async () => {
     if (!supabase) throw new Error('Supabase is not configured');
     const { data, error } = await supabase
       .from('user_events')
       .select('events(id, slug, template_id, content_config, event_date, automation_config, status, partner1_name, partner2_name)');
     if (error) throw error;
     return (data ?? []).map(row => row.events).filter(Boolean);
   };
   ```
   Sort client-side after fetch (per research — avoids Supabase foreignTable ordering pitfall):
   ```javascript
   // Sort by event_date DESC, fallback to empty string for nulls
   const sorted = results.sort((a, b) => (b.event_date || '').localeCompare(a.event_date || ''));
   ```

2. `fetchAllEvents()` — fetches ALL events for super admins:
   ```javascript
   export const fetchAllEvents = async () => {
     if (!supabase) throw new Error('Supabase is not configured');
     const { data, error } = await supabase
       .from('events')
       .select('id, slug, template_id, content_config, event_date, automation_config, status, partner1_name, partner2_name')
       .order('event_date', { ascending: false });
     if (error) throw error;
     return data ?? [];
   };
   ```

**In `src/contexts/AuthContext.tsx`** — extend to fetch and expose `isSuperAdmin`:

1. Add `isSuperAdmin: boolean` to `AuthContextValue` interface.
2. Add state: `const [isSuperAdmin, setIsSuperAdmin] = useState(false);`
3. Add a separate `useEffect` that runs when `session?.user?.id` changes:
   - If no user ID, set `isSuperAdmin` to `false` and return.
   - Query `supabase.from('users').select('is_super_admin').eq('id', session.user.id).single()`.
   - Set `isSuperAdmin` from `data?.is_super_admin ?? false`.
   - On error, default to `false` (fail closed).
4. Include `isSuperAdmin` in the Provider value object.
5. Keep the `loading` state accurate — `isSuperAdmin` fetch should not block initial auth loading (it's a secondary fetch). The `loading` flag covers session resolution only.
  </action>
  <verify>
    <automated>npx tsc --noEmit 2>&1 | head -30</automated>
  </verify>
